library(Seurat)
library(Matrix)
swhite_05 <- Read10X(data.dir = "/home/rstudio/time-series/umi-counts/white_05_inex")
barcodes=read.table(file = "/home/rstudio/time-series/files/white_05/barcodes.6000.txt",header = FALSE,sep = "\n")
swhite_05=swhite_05[,barcodes$V1]
swhite_05=CreateSeuratObject(swhite_05)

# Add latent space
lwhite_05 <- read.csv("/home/rstudio/time-series/latent_space/white_05.csv", row.names=1)
lwhite_05=as.matrix(lwhite_05)
rownames(lwhite_05)=rownames(swhite_05@meta.data)
swhite_05[["scVI"]] <- CreateDimReducObject(embeddings =lwhite_05,key = "scVI_")
No assay specified, setting assay as RNA by default.
# Generate UMAP
swhite_05=RunUMAP(swhite_05,reduction="scVI",dims = 1:10)

# No visualize empty droplets because I have already chosen top 6000 barcodes
# which is the number of cells I had targeted. So my assumption is that there are no emtpy barcodes in top 6000.

# Visualize doublets from doublet detection
# As this is a fairly homogenous cell type, I am using UMI cutoff as the criteria for removing doublets
# doublets= barcodes with UMI count > mean(UMI count) + 2* standard deviation (UMI count)
dwhite_05 <-rownames(swhite_05@meta.data)[swhite_05$nCount_RNA>mean(swhite_05$nCount_RNA)+2*sd(swhite_05$nCount_RNA)]

# Visualize percent mt content
swhite_05[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(swhite_05, pattern = "^MT-")
FeaturePlot(swhite_05,c("percent.mt"))

swhite_05=FindNeighbors(swhite_05,reduction="scVI",graph.name="RNA_snn_scVI",dims=1:10)
Computing nearest neighbor graph
Computing SNN
swhite_05=FindClusters(swhite_05,resolution = seq(.1, .6, by = 0.1),graph.name = "RNA_snn_scVI", verbose = FALSE)

# Visualize cells clustered at different resolutions
library(ggplot2)
p=list(length(seq(.1, .6, by = 0.1)))
x=1
for (i in seq(.1, .6, by = 0.1)) {
  col.name=colnames(swhite_05@meta.data)[match(paste("RNA_snn_scVI_res",i,sep = "."),colnames(swhite_05@meta.data))]
  p[[x]]=UMAPPlot(swhite_05,group.by=col.name,label=TRUE)+ggtitle(col.name)
  x=x+1
}
library(gridExtra)
n <- length(p)
nCol <- floor(sqrt(n))
#do.call("grid.arrange", c(p, ncol=nCol))
# At resolution .4, reasonable clustering is observed. 
Idents(swhite_05)="RNA_snn_scVI_res.0.4"
UMAPPlot(swhite_05,label=TRUE,label.size=6)+theme_classic(base_size = 20)+theme(legend.position = "none",axis.title.x=element_blank(),axis.title.y=element_blank())

library(dplyr)
swhite_05@meta.data %>% group_by(RNA_snn_scVI_res.0.4) %>% summarise(mean(percent.mt))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
swhite_05@meta.data %>% group_by(RNA_snn_scVI_res.0.4) %>% summarise(mean(nCount_RNA))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
# So far, it looks like cluster 0 cells have high mitochondrial content.
# Does DE analysis also confirms the same?
# Ans: Yes. Cluster 0 cells only have MT genes enriched even with logFC > 0.5. Cluster 1 cells on the other hand have no gene DE at logFC > 0.5 as compared to cluster 0 cells. This suggests that cluster 0 cells are the same as cluster 1 cells with high MT content, possibly because of MT debris attached (?)
# I also checked the mean UMI count and it is higher in cluster 0 than cluster 1, suggesting that cluster 0 cells may have nuclei along with attached debris, as compared to just MT-debris (background RNA)
x=FindMarkers(object = swhite_05,ident.1 = 1,ident.2 = 0,logfc.threshold = .5,only.pos = TRUE)
Error in FindMarkers.default(object = data.use, slot = data.slot, counts = counts,  : 
  No features pass logfc.threshold threshold

To remove cluster with high MT content, cluster 0 will be removed. However, some cells in cluster 2 are also high MT-content therefore sub-clustering on cluster 0.

s_subset=subset(swhite_05,cells=WhichCells(swhite_05,idents = 2))
s_subset=FindNeighbors(s_subset,reduction="scVI",graph.name="RNA_snn_scVI",dims=1:10)
Computing nearest neighbor graph
Computing SNN
s_subset=FindClusters(s_subset,resolution = .1,graph.name = "RNA_snn_scVI", verbose = FALSE)
UMAPPlot(s_subset)

s_subset@meta.data %>% group_by(RNA_snn_scVI_res.0.1) %>% summarise(mean(percent.mt))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
# Even after subclustering of cluster 2, a tiny bit of cluster next to adipocytes, are still part of the same cluster. 
# Check what percent.mt content there
FeaturePlot(s_subset,"percent.mt")


# Therefore, one way to remove these cells is to remove all barcodes with MT content > mean (MT content in cells already annotated as bad)
mt.bad=WhichCells(swhite_05,idents = 0)
mt.bad=union(mt.bad,WhichCells(s_subset,idents = 0))
mt.bad=union(mt.bad,rownames(swhite_05@meta.data)[swhite_05$percent.mt>mean(swhite_05@meta.data[mt.bad,"percent.mt"])])
UMAPPlot(swhite_05,cells.highlight=mt.bad)

# Remove doublets and low-quality barcodes
bwhite_05=rownames(swhite_05@meta.data)
bwhite_05=setdiff(bwhite_05,union(mt.bad,dwhite_05))
UMAPPlot(swhite_05,cells.highlight=bwhite_05)

swhite_05=subset(swhite_05,cells = bwhite_05)
UMAPPlot(swhite_05)
